== 3...e5 ==
This is the most common and ambitious reply by Black. This move attacks White's centre and opens up the dark-squared bishop.

There is only one move that preserves White's advantage, that being '''[[/4. Nf3/]]''', attacking e5 and defending d4.

'''4. Bxc4?''' doesn't work due to 4...Qxd4! 5. Qxd4 exd4 6. Nf3 c5 {{Chess/not|-}} and Black is able to build a fairly stable centre.

'''4. dxe5?''' also does not work due to 4...Qxd1!, forcing a trade of queens with Kxd1, and although material is even, White is exposed in the center and loses castling rights.

=== History ===
The first occurence of this variation is in 1834 in a game between [[w:Alexander McDonell|Alexander McDonell]] and [[w:Louis de La Bourdonnais|Louis de La Bourdonnais]].<ref>{{cite web
|url=https://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1001153
|website=www.chessgames.com
|title=La Bourdonnais - McDonnell, 1834}}</ref> White continued with 4. d5, which is not seen nowadays because it overextends White's centre which Black can easily undermine with moves like ...c6 and ...Bb4.

